		<title type="html"><![CDATA[New Discoveries]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.madelinedowney.com/2010/12/new-discoveries/" />
		<id>http://www.madelinedowney.com/?p=422</id>
		<updated>2010-12-09T05:32:47Z</updated>
		<published>2010-12-09T04:23:13Z</published>
		<category scheme="http://www.madelinedowney.com" term="Rants" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[Greetings, fellow Earthlings, both phosphorous and arsenic-based! Now that I have achieved my triple missions of finding alien life forms, releasing secret government documents, and using the potty, I&#8217;m back and ready to tell you all about it. I&#8217;ve had some incredible adventures over the last several months — I traveled to several new places, [...]]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.madelinedowney.com/2010/12/new-discoveries/"><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://www.madelinedowney.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/DSC_7119-550x365.jpg" alt="" title="drawin" width="550" height="365" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-450" /></p>
<p>Greetings, fellow Earthlings, both phosphorous and <a href="http://latestendeavor.com/nasa-announcement-unveils-arsenic-surviving-bacteria/351704">arsenic-based</a>! Now that I have achieved my triple missions of finding alien life forms, releasing secret government documents, and using the potty, I&#8217;m back and ready to tell you all about it.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve had some incredible adventures over the last several months — I traveled to several new places, met countless kitties, puppies and fishies, enjoyed numerous zoos, and experienced the wonders of holidays and snow. Along the way I picked up some skills, obsessions, and silly phrases.</p>
<h2>New Skills</h2>
<p>My dad and I go to Meijer a lot on the weekends, because mom needs to sleep in. Plus we&#8217;re probably out of butter, since I find it necessary to eat butter directly from the jar with a spoon. Anyway, I&#8217;ve decided that I&#8217;m employed at Meijer now, so here&#8217;s some of the skills I listed on my résumé; take note, college grads!</p>
<ol>
<li>Keeping a &#8220;close eye&#8221; on an item by moving my face within the immediate proximity of said item.</li>
<li>Building towers with magnet tiles and then subsequently destroying them, using the contradictory practices of Zen non-attachment and destructive arm flailing.</li>
<li>Navigating an iPhone with the prowess of a New York hipster (but absent the beards and poorly conceived irony.)</li>
<li>Asserting my independence by noticeably objecting to wintertime attire of any sort.</li>
<li>Counting, identifying numbers and letters, drawing, painting, and saying goofy words like &#8220;rhinoceros,&#8221; &#8220;jellybeans&#8221; and &#8220;stinkypants.&#8221;</li>
<li>Swimming in hotel pools — evidently hotels are the only places with aquatic facilities.</li>
<li>Spotting spiders from 30 feet away, and demanding that a cleanup action be taken at once!</li>
<li>Clever naming: I have coined many excellent names for my various inanimate friends. Examples: Opie and Eight (dolls), Alli (stuffed cat), Avery (weird jumpy lumberjack toy from a Happy Meal), Peter (any computer), Bubby The P.U. Fish (a smelly plastic bath toy.)
<li>Diaper-free life: I decided to ditch the diapers once and for all, and use the potty full-time. Sure, it&#8217;s nice not to pee in one&#8217;s pants, but my primary motivation was to sit in the bathroom at length and put stickers all over everything.</li>
</ol>
<h2>New Obsessions</h2>
<p>What can I say? I get hooked on stuff.</p>
<ol>
<li>The Funny Dude: our neighbors put out a motorized robot corpse for Halloween, and after naming it &#8220;The Funny Dude&#8221; I became incredibly fascinated with him. So much so that I was still requesting access to The Funny Dude well after he was stowed away and the local kids&#8217; Halloween cavities were filled.</li>
<li>Planes, barking dogs, and The Moon: if I hear any noise or see any sky-based objects outside, I demand to see it! I demand satisfaction! <em>This is entirely problematic at 3:00am — Ed.</em></li>
<li>Tiny things: little stuff is the best. I seek out the smallest individual squares from our various puzzle board games. I prefer the wee baby in my Russian nesting doll set. During my frequent excursions (shifts) at Meijer, I pick up miniature stuffed animals and often convince dad to bring one of them home, then I insist on having all of them in my bed at night. And finally, I love dominos — both for stacking and holding them to my ear, like tiny domino telephones.</li>
</ol>
<h2>New Silly Phrases</h2>
<p>There are almost too many to count, but I need to work on counting anyway. 1, 3, 6, 7&#8230;</p>
<ol>
<li>I add &#8220;eeyoo!&#8221; to the end of people&#8217;s names. Examples: Mommyoo, Daddyoo, Maddieyoo, Debbieyoo, etc.</li>
<li>I like to yell for my parents by their real names. &#8220;KATE!&#8221;</li>
<li>I demonstrate my resolute independence by responding, &#8220;no, fine&#8221; any time you try to help me with something, particularly when meals, clothing or toothbrushing are involved.</li>
<li>Also on the clothing front, almost all clothes are &#8220;too tight&#8221; even when they are sweatpants.</li>
<li>When something is of grave concern, such as the noise made by a leaky bathtub drain, I become quite worried and whine, &#8220;don&#8217;t like it!&#8221;</li>
<li>I&#8217;m pretty clever, but sometimes I don&#8217;t understand what you&#8217;re going on about. In those cases, I simply respond &#8220;yeah&#8221; and hope you won&#8217;t notice. For example: &#8220;Maddie, what&#8217;s the name of that Orangutan?&#8221; &#8220;Yeah.&#8221;</li>
<li>I have a penchant for funny talking, which is exactly like regular talking, except lower and more drawn out. KAYWTEE</li>
<li>It is extremely difficult to record me via standard photographic means due to my insistence upon watching the recording you didn&#8217;t get to take. I request this by stating, &#8220;I see I see I see!&#8221;</li>
</ol>
<p>Until next time, Peops!</p>
]]></content>
